5|$|In 2006, {{because of}} the {{implosion}} of the <b>cooling</b> <b>tower</b> at Trojan Nuclear Power Plant, a group got together in the South Park Blocks and brought down a 25-foot model tower to celebrate the implosion.|$|E
25|$|HVAC {{use of a}} <b>cooling</b> <b>tower</b> pairs the <b>cooling</b> <b>tower</b> with a {{water-cooled}} chiller or water-cooled condenser. A ton of air-conditioning {{is defined}} as the removal of 12,000 BTU/hour (3500 W). The equivalent ton on the <b>cooling</b> <b>tower</b> side actually rejects about 15,000 BTU/hour (4400 W) due to the additional waste heat-equivalent of the energy needed to drive the chiller's compressor. This equivalent ton {{is defined as the}} heat rejection in cooling 3 US gallons/minute (1,500 pound/hour) of water 10°F (6°C), which amounts to 15,000 BTU/hour, assuming a chiller coefficient of performance (COP) of 4.0. This COP is equivalent to an energy efficiency ratio (EER) of 14.|$|E
